     <br>
     This game will never get me addicted simply because my life is too busy.  While some of the things that make it busy aren't pleasant, which do lead me to rather be playing than living life, most aren't.  I have a lot of friends that I regularly go out with, two nieces that I devote a lot of time to, a girlfriend I'm very happy with....etc.  Those things, while EQ is fun, are much more fufilling to me than EQ could ever be.  BUT...if those things were to go away and my life not so full....who knows.  Honestly, I probably would stay on EQ all the time at that point.  I mean really....why wouldn't I?  <br>
<br>
The problem is that people want to put blame on other things not under their control as to why their loved ones shut them out in favor of a game, rather than accept any responsibility themselves.  The statements about parents needing to introduce other activities is a good one.  Put more pleasant things in front of the child so that they have other &quot;escapes&quot; than just the game.  But it still comes down to the fact that if the person has an inherantly addictive personality, or EQ is simply better and more fufilling than their real life, they will choose the game (or any game) over that life.  It's not the game...it's YOU. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
