       All things in moderation is a great idea, but I have to disagree with our classic moderator Mysidia, in that, you do not need to have an addictive personality to become addicted to something.   There are always people who seem to be an exception to any rule, but for the most part I am sure not all cigarette smokers, heroin addicts and chronic food munchers have addictive personalities.  The body is a strange and complex machine and we often dont know the effects of certain things until later on.  The example of running given ( I will paraphrase because I am hopped up on crack atm and cant remember the exact phrasing) is a valid one,  runners can often become &quot;addicted&quot; to the endorphin high they get from pushing themselves as far as they can and can suffer withdrawls from stopping their running.  The same goes for peopel who eat alot of hot stuff ( chilis, tobasco etc) because of teh endorphin rush caused by the &quot;heat&quot;.<br>
         A lot of you seem to be able to play without issue, and i think that is great, but not everyone has the same relationship with EQ.  While I have not seen withdrawls from eq ( no one I know has successfully quit yet), I have seen some of the life penalties from constant play.  Chronic joblessness, execessive procrastination as well as the unintentional destruction of personal relationships that can occur by shutting people out to engage in a computer game.  I think it is a mistake to catagorically get defensive about EQ being addictive, and maybe look at the bigger picture as far as how we spend our time, and if from a distance we would be proud of what we do.  If you told me three years ago that I would have logged 140 days in a game, out of my real life, I would have said that you were crazy.. and no way... But sure enough here I sit..  Maybe you can handle it, but some people cant.  I am sure it is not EQ specifically, but maybe a time vs decreasing reward games in general, in which EQ just happens to reign supreme at the moment.  Laws etc.. regulating addictive substances are a joke for the most part and do nothing to help the &quot;problem&quot;,self education can though.  I salute you for delving into the issue, and maybe if more people were honest with themselves and did not feel so defensive, more people could have the best of both worlds.  Phat L3wtz, A great guild, and a real life that is as rewarding as their virtual one. <br>
