Once again - this is the problem that I was referring too.  You see little to gain from everquest so addiction to it is a problem.  Other people see very little to gain from Cross Country, so addiction to it would be a problem.  Who gets to judge what is harmful and what isn't?  Personally, I would much rather have people addicted to EQ than I would to television or even a strenuous sport.<br>
<br>
For instance - after taking many learning tests, I have been told that I learn by pattern recognition.  I have also been told that I am pretty good at it.  Personally, I attribute a large part of that to my video game playing.  Many of the same skills that I use every day to interpret difficult math problems game from playing video games.  I can guarentee without having grown up with video games I would have never learned to program, I would have never learned to fix computers, and I would not have been able to support my family with those skills.  Why?  Because each of those activities started as a direct result of a challenge facing me in a video game.<br>
<br>
So who is to say that there is little to learn from EQ?  Especially in a world where physical strength and mechanical apptitude are quickly being replaced by computer operating skills and quick decision making as highly desirable qualities.<br>
<br>
