<br>
At one point in time I let my life slip a bit and wasnt paying bills, was showing up to work late or calling in, but I recall I was going thru a divorce at that time.  Granted it was a divorce that I had filed for and requested but it is a tough time no less.  I considered at that time was I addicted to a video game?  Answer: No.  It was a release.  My characters life wasnt going thru the same drama my RL was going thru and no one even knew I was going thru it.  Where as in RL everyone asks 20 questions and reminds you all the more how things are going.  So all of my time went into game.<br>
<br>
And now a year later, I play in the evenings after I get done attending a full time job and all my bills get paid.  Im raising my 16 year old brother.  I have a RL but still play EQ.  When it comes down to it, if Im not working (working as in house and job) what else is there to do?  I could be like the rest of the world and watch sitcoms all night.  I guess then I could be considered &quot;normal.&quot;  I do not attend a Christian church.  I do not drink so no cause to go to bars.  If I went to one movie it is the cost I can pay for EQ for an entire month, and thats WITH OUT popcorn, soda, and a friend. 2 hours of entertainment vs. my own schedule permitting an entire month.<br>
<br>
EQ saves me cash.  And I get to socialize with people I would never other wise get a chance to do so.  I live in Missouri, and my friends all play from California, Nevada, etc.  I have had friends in S. Korea and Singapore.  Even gotten to know them on a first name basis and about thier RL and families.  So those who think we are addicted to a &quot;fantasy&quot; also have it false.<br>
<br>
And btw Rani hit the nail on the head.  I too started playing EQ to find something in common to do with my husband.  Those who are bent out of shape cause thier significant other does not spend so much time with them are sorta being selfish.  Stop whining and if they mean that much to you, YOU try to find a way to meet them half way.  You would be suprised that they would realize the effort and try one of your hobbies with you.<br>
<br>
Hope my opinion helps you on your paper, you may look into the evidence supporting the non-addiction.  Just off the top of my head if you go to castersrealm there was an article linked the news pages about a woman whos daughter died while locked in a car as she played everquest.  There was a psychologist on there who claims RPG's are not addictive.  My opinion is the same.  <br>
